[1
Date: Sat, 17 Jan 1998 16:20:02 WST
From: Denis Green <snoigel@hotmail.com>
Source: <http://www.infobeat.com/stories/cgi/story.cgi?id=6983393-4cd>

16 January 1998: Swine fever outbreak forces German pig cull
The slaughter of tens of thousands of pigs began Friday after an outbreak
of swine fever was detected at one of Germany's biggest piggeries. Farm
authorities in northeastern Germany said all the estimated 62,000 animals
at the farm near the town of Bad Kleinen in the state of
Mecklenberg-Vorpommern would have to be killed at a cost of around $5.5
million. As many as 15,000 pigs in Lower Saxony, 7,600 in North
Rhine-Westphalia and up to 3,500 in Schleswig-Holstein might also have to
be culled even though there was no sign yet that the disease had broken out
there, state authorities said.
--
Denis Green
